work was carried out on Churchill's Hut with a grant provided by Tourism
Tasmania.&nbsp; Photo courtesy: Col Bailey.</font></font></center>
</td>
</tr>
</table></center>

<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unfortunately, in late
January 2019, a huge bushfire raging in the Tasmanian South-West wilderness
destroyed the hut.&nbsp; The fires were unstoppable, and despite a complex
sprinkler system installed by the Primary Industries, Parks, Water &amp;
Environment Department to protect the hut, a sudden wind change swept the
fire rapidly down upon the ancient structure, burning it to the ground.&nbsp;
Workmen attending the sprinkler system were forced to flee for their lives,
and fortunately, no one was injured.</font>
<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Churchill's hut is permanently
entered on the Tasmanian Heritage Register, recognised because of its historical
significance in telling the stories of thylacine trappers who lived and
worked in remote locations in Tasmania's highlands.</font>
<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Previously standing
in an idyllic setting, the former hut it is now a somber sight - all that
remains being the iron roof resting upon the charred remnants of the timbered
structure, surrounded by a forest of blackened trees.&nbsp; It is unknown
at this stage if the hut will be rebuilt.</font></td>
</tr>
</table></center>
<font color="#FFFFFF">.</font></td>
</tr>
</table></center>
<font color="#666666">.</font>
